post_text:
Good afternoon Stevensville students and families,

Stevensville Schools want to communicate that we are working hard on our re-entry plan for fall.

We have reviewed survey results from parents and staff and built a rough framework for re-entry, which is getting altered constantly with our ever changing situation. We are also building a plan that is specific for our schools in our small community. Final edits are underway.

Please know that Stevensville Schools will have a plan out very soon, after our staff reviews it. Then, there will be a special board meeting to adopt the plan.

Stevensville Schools are committed to the safety and well being of our students. We are building a plan that we feel will fit the needs of most families.

Thank you for your patience and understanding as we work through this process. Thank you for your support in education and for our students.

Go Jackets!

Good afternoon students and parents,

In regards to letter grades or pass/fail marks, it‚Äôs a system where you have to chooses one or the other. You can‚Äôt choose a couple classes of letter grades and the rest pass/fail. It has to be all letter grades or all pass/fail marks.

I just wanted to take a minute to clarify this, so there were no misconceptions of the process. Also, before deciding which option you prefer, I recommend that the student and their parents, sit down and figure out which option is the best for their own personal situation. Every students situation is unique, which is why we are instituting this option.

Thanks,

Principal Gum

post_text:
For students enrolled in MTDA the following information was sent out today. If you have questions or concerns send me an email. -Mrs. Wohlman

High School Original Credit

High school original credit courses will remain available in our online classrooms during the closure. We have asked all of our teachers to make sure all assignments are open for completion through April, but, at this point, we will not enforce any short-term deadlines in the course. Our teachers will be available to connect with students via email. We are also asking our teachers to continue to stay in touch with their students over the next two weeks to help provide connection and emotional support.

High School Credit Recovery

Our credit recovery program will pause until March 27, 2020, and course courses themselves will be closed during that time. Please do not distribute passwords, per our school guidelines. MTDA staff will evaluate the situation daily and determine our next actions with credit recovery as the situation evolves.

post_text: Beginning Tuesday, March 17 lunch and breakfast will be delivered to students. Our kitchen staff will prepare sack meals. Meals will be delivered daily via morning bus routes at the usual prescribed pickup time. We ask that students/families meet the bus to pick up sack meals. Meals will be delivered on both Friday and Monday even though students were not scheduled to attend. If you cannot meet the scheduled bus time or if students do not utilize bus services, the District will provide grab and go meals. These meals are available from 10:00 am to 12:00 at the Burnt Fork Market parking lot and the bus stop at the corner of Illinois Bench and Airport Roads. The backpack food program will continue on Fridays. These packs will be prepared, labeled for recipients, and available to students on the morning bus routes and grab and go locations Fridays. Please check school website, building Facebook pages and email for updates.

post_text:
Dear Families,

Governor Bullock has announced that all public schools will close for 2 weeks (March 16-27, 2020). The administrative team will be meeting on Monday, March 16, 2020 to determine District actions and responses. All students are not to report to school during this closure. This includes all community facility use and school activities (clubs, athletics, driver‚Äôs ed, adult ed, etc.). The District will be determining a plan for student meals as directed by the Governor‚Äôs Office.

The District will be notifying the school community of actions we will take to address the educational and nutritional needs of our students. The Board and administration will determine actions and procedures based on the direction of Ravalli County Public Health Department, the Center for Disease Control, the Governor‚Äôs Office, and the Office of Public Instruction.

Please monitor Infinite Campus and news media releases for future messages regarding this matter.

Thank you,
Dr. Moore

Tracey Rogstad
Principal grades 4-8
Stevensville Middle School
